=== verdicts vs declared expectations (docstring) ===
1. HEADLINE, fixed shared budget of 1000 updates (all modes at K=10), per-seed PAIRED split/birth loss ratios: ['767x', '18x', '493x']
   -> the composite birth growth rule beats this split baseline by >=10x on every seed at the shared budget.
   auxiliary (one-off, 4000 iters): final ratios ['61x', '85x', '52x']
   note: split runs DO end with negative weights (the optimizer drags weights through zero); splitting itself never flips a sign (tested directly).
2. attribution ablation, PAIRED per seed (only the newborn's initial weight differs; placement/scale/method shared with 'birth'):
   iter 1000: birth_pos/birth per seed ['0.992', '1.014', '0.926']  paired median 0.992x
   iter 1000: birth_zero/birth per seed ['0.140', '0.842', '0.861']  paired median 0.842x
   final (auxiliary): birth_pos/birth per seed ['3.815', '1.174', '1.463']  paired median 1.463x
   final (auxiliary): birth_zero/birth per seed ['0.148', '0.528', '0.994']  paired median 0.528x
   -> sign injection is NOT a main factor: forced-positive and zero-init newborns land within small factors of signed ones (paired medians above). What these data support: the COMPOSITE birth rule (placement + initial scale + generation method) beats this split baseline; attributing the gain to placement ALONE would need a separate scale/position ablation, not run here.
